WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.480
The most exciting thing that you're working on right now is that as an engineering manager

00:00:08.480 --> 00:00:14.540
for Posit, which formerly known as RStudio, and the makers of RStudio, you're now working

00:00:14.540 --> 00:00:19.400
there as an engineering manager and your project that you're leading the development of is

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:25.799
something called Positron, which is described as a next generation IDE, integrated development

00:00:25.799 --> 00:00:27.639
environment, for data science.

00:00:27.639 --> 00:00:30.320
So that is what RStudio was many years ago.

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:40.840
I mean, I was using RStudio since 2007, that I can kind of at least since then.

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:46.720
And it was definitely my go to IDE when I was primarily an R developer back then, an

00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:55.240
R data scientist, although I guess I wouldn't have used the word data scientist in 2007.

00:00:55.240 --> 00:01:02.599
And so with Positron, what are the gaps or limitations that you're addressing that aren't

00:01:02.599 --> 00:01:06.519
covered by things like RStudio, VS Code, or Jupyter Notebooks, which might be the go to

00:01:06.519 --> 00:01:09.959
IDEs for data scientists or software developers today?

00:01:09.959 --> 00:01:10.959
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:01:10.959 --> 00:01:11.959
Yeah.

00:01:11.959 --> 00:01:18.320
If I was going to sum up the one gap I feel like that Positron is working to address,

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:23.080
it's that there isn't something out there right now that can be one place you go to

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:24.580
do all your data science.

00:01:24.580 --> 00:01:29.059
So Positron is not a general purpose IDE.

00:01:29.059 --> 00:01:32.739
It is specifically an IDE built to do data science.

00:01:32.739 --> 00:01:39.580
And I come from a science background, and I've always been someone who wrote code for

00:01:39.580 --> 00:01:40.580
my data analysis.

00:01:40.580 --> 00:01:46.820
But I've always really felt that my needs were a little different than someone who is

00:01:46.820 --> 00:01:52.459
writing general purpose code, like to build a website or to make a mobile app.

00:01:52.459 --> 00:01:56.300
People who write code to analyze data are different in some real ways.

00:01:56.300 --> 00:02:05.220
It's not that it's like they're worse coders or like, no, no, I really do think that.

00:02:05.220 --> 00:02:06.220
It's not.

00:02:06.220 --> 00:02:07.220
It's not.

00:02:07.220 --> 00:02:10.820
I don't think it is that people who write code to analyze data do a worse job writing

00:02:10.820 --> 00:02:11.820
code.

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:15.740
It's that their needs are different and that they're writing code in a different way.

00:02:15.740 --> 00:02:22.179
So folks who have been, for example, who have been using VS Code as a data science

00:02:22.179 --> 00:02:26.699
IDE have really felt that tension where they're like, this is really general purpose.

00:02:26.699 --> 00:02:31.979
And instead, I'm trying to kind of customizing it using extensions to fit my needs.

00:02:31.979 --> 00:02:36.179
So Positron is meant to specifically be a data science IDE.

00:02:36.179 --> 00:02:43.500
Positron is also like a real driving reason why we've built it the way it is, is that

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:47.059
it is a multilingual or polyglot IDE.

00:02:47.059 --> 00:02:52.220
A lot of the environments you might download to do scientific computing or data science

00:02:52.220 --> 00:02:55.940
or data analysis are built specifically for one language.

00:02:55.940 --> 00:02:57.619
So I know all of us have used these.

00:02:57.619 --> 00:03:04.660
So RStudio is an example of one of these, like MATLAB, Spyder, there are a lot of environments

00:03:04.660 --> 00:03:08.779
in which you would do data analysis that are just built for one language.

00:03:08.779 --> 00:03:13.779
And increasingly, I just think that's not how many people, that's not how as many people

00:03:13.779 --> 00:03:14.779
work.

00:03:14.779 --> 00:03:19.059
Many, many people use multiple languages, whether it's on one project that literally

00:03:19.059 --> 00:03:23.899
uses multiple languages over the course of a week, they pick up different projects that

00:03:23.899 --> 00:03:29.820
use different languages or almost certainly on the span of years or your career, you use

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:32.380
different languages because things change in our ecosystem.

00:03:32.380 --> 00:03:36.179
Like you said, you started with R and now you use other languages.

00:03:36.179 --> 00:03:41.660
There are so many people who use combinations of R and Rust, or they work on projects that's

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:48.460
like Python plus front-end kind of technologies, JavaScript, HTML, et cetera, or like almost

00:03:48.460 --> 00:03:51.419
any data science language plus SQL.

00:03:51.419 --> 00:03:57.139
Very few people, an IDE that is built to use one language, for very few people, is that

00:03:57.139 --> 00:04:01.139
really going to fit all of the needs that they have over the course of a week, a month,

00:04:01.139 --> 00:04:03.539
or multiple years.

00:04:03.539 --> 00:04:09.860
So Positron is built with a design such that the front-end user phasing features are about

00:04:09.860 --> 00:04:16.779
the tasks you need to do, like whether that is interactively write code, whether that's

00:04:16.779 --> 00:04:23.179
dealing with your plots, whether that's seeing, exploring your data in a visual way.

00:04:23.179 --> 00:04:27.459
And then there are backend language packs that provide the engines for those front-end

00:04:27.459 --> 00:04:28.459
features.

00:04:28.459 --> 00:04:31.980
So Positron, it's very early days for Positron.

00:04:31.980 --> 00:04:36.700
We only made it public about six weeks ago, as of the day we're recording this.

00:04:36.700 --> 00:04:42.100
So it is currently shipping with support for Python and R, but it is designed in such a

00:04:42.100 --> 00:04:49.820
way that other data science languages can be added, because there's a separation between

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:53.040
the front-end features and what is driving them.

00:04:53.040 --> 00:04:59.739
So we look forward to adding support for other languages as we collaborate with other data

00:04:59.739 --> 00:05:07.339
science communities, or new things come up, like new exciting ways of doing data science

00:05:07.339 --> 00:05:08.339
come up.

00:05:08.339 --> 00:05:09.339
Nice.

00:05:09.339 --> 00:05:11.459
So the polyglot IDE part to me, that makes a huge amount of sense.

00:05:11.459 --> 00:05:14.899
I get that especially as a contrast to RStudio.

00:05:14.899 --> 00:05:19.380
For people who are writing code as a data analyst or data scientist, people who are

00:05:19.380 --> 00:05:24.859
working with data, what is different that we need specifically relative to another software

00:05:24.859 --> 00:05:25.859
developer?

00:05:25.859 --> 00:05:26.859
Yeah.

00:05:26.980 --> 00:05:34.660
I think one piece that is very different is that the process of writing code is more exploratory,

00:05:34.660 --> 00:05:35.940
is more interactive.

00:05:35.940 --> 00:05:38.299
And that's not wrong or bad.

00:05:38.299 --> 00:05:42.820
That is actually just the fact that instead of getting a spec from a product manager and

00:05:42.820 --> 00:05:48.619
building a product, like that's not what data scientists, data analysts do.

00:05:48.619 --> 00:05:55.700
You start with data and you often don't know what you can or should do in detail until

00:05:55.700 --> 00:05:57.500
you start that process.

00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:03.779
And if you have a code writing process that is more exploratory, you need more supports

00:06:03.779 --> 00:06:07.420
for writing in that interactive exploratory mode.

00:06:07.420 --> 00:06:14.140
Some things that support that are things like a truly, truly fully featured interactive

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:15.140
console.

00:06:15.140 --> 00:06:18.459
Of course that does exist in various ways.

00:06:18.459 --> 00:06:24.100
People get at that in various ways, like when they use notebooks or using say a Python REPL.

00:06:24.100 --> 00:06:30.739
But if you get to a truly, fully featured interactive console where what happens in

00:06:30.739 --> 00:06:38.179
the console is then reflected in the rest of where you're working, like say in Positron

00:06:38.179 --> 00:06:39.940
we have what we call a variables pane.

00:06:39.940 --> 00:06:43.619
If you come from our studio, you may be familiar with something called an environment pane

00:06:43.619 --> 00:06:45.899
where you see all the things you've...

00:06:45.899 --> 00:06:50.019
And it updates as you change things or the plots that you see.

00:06:50.019 --> 00:06:51.179
You have them all right there.

00:06:51.179 --> 00:06:53.279
You can scroll through them.

00:06:53.279 --> 00:06:56.000
If you change and make a new plot, you see it pop up there.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.720
And you have that really interactive way of working.

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:07.480
Some of the other things that I know really make a difference for people help inside of

00:07:07.480 --> 00:07:09.119
the IDE where you are working.

00:07:09.119 --> 00:07:10.119
So you don't...

00:07:10.119 --> 00:07:14.359
You know, you're working along, you're like, ah, wait, what is the function signature?

00:07:14.359 --> 00:07:16.980
Or maybe I want to look at the docs for this.

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:22.959
So instead of having to get out of a flow state and go somewhere else and read docs,

00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:28.679
like on the website, you can open up help right there and copy paste, like go right

00:07:28.679 --> 00:07:33.040
back and forth and stay in that kind of flow state.

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:35.660
Another thing is you're building interactive apps.

00:07:35.660 --> 00:07:41.480
You need a way to have that right there and that it updates as you change your code versus

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:46.119
having some sort of build process, going somewhere, looking at a browser.

00:07:46.119 --> 00:07:52.839
There's really quite a lot that if we put it together, we can make people more productive.

00:07:53.720 --> 00:08:01.440
The company that I work for, Posit, the company formerly known as RStudio, Posit, it's a really

00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:08.040
fun place to work as someone who likes thinking about the process that people bring to their

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:09.040
tasks.

00:08:09.040 --> 00:08:14.920
Because I do think, like, we are huge believers in code-first data science.

00:08:14.920 --> 00:08:18.279
Not no-code solutions, not GUI-based tool.

00:08:18.279 --> 00:08:22.119
People who do data work should be writing code.

00:08:22.119 --> 00:08:25.320
And at the same time, their needs are different, like their needs are different.

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:31.000
And so we can, like pretty much every single thing my company does is like deeply informed

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:37.640
by this belief or like how deeply we know that data practitioners are different and

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:42.239
that's good and fine and we can make them more productive by building tools that are

00:08:42.239 --> 00:08:45.080
specifically for the kinds of tasks they need to do.

00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:46.080
Very nice.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:51.440
And yes, so not only do you have Code OSS as a kind of a backbone that's providing building

00:08:51.520 --> 00:08:55.440
blocks for Positron and offering that kind of extensibility through all the VS Code extensions,

00:08:55.440 --> 00:08:59.359
like you mentioned Databricks there, any number of extensions that people might want to be

00:08:59.359 --> 00:09:00.359
able to import.

00:09:00.359 --> 00:09:05.039
Rainbow tabs, whatever you want, it's out there.

00:09:05.039 --> 00:09:10.280
In addition to all those things, the Positron project itself is open source.

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:15.200
So if people are listening and they want to be contributing, right now at the time of

00:09:15.200 --> 00:09:20.200
recording there are 27 people, including I can see your face as one of those GitHub contributors.

00:09:20.239 --> 00:09:24.119
So any of those contributors can go and they can contribute to this developing and very

00:09:24.119 --> 00:09:25.119
exciting project.

00:09:25.119 --> 00:09:26.119
Yeah, yeah.

00:09:26.119 --> 00:09:31.000
So Positron is licensed such that it is source available.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:36.080
Anyone can come and look at the source, change it, contribute to it, and it is also licensed

00:09:36.080 --> 00:09:40.640
such that it is free to use for, including for commercial purposes.

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:45.359
Like you can use it, of course, in academia for personal projects, but you can use it

00:09:45.359 --> 00:09:46.359
at work.

00:09:46.359 --> 00:09:53.080
So it's licensed in such a way that it is free to use in your work as a data scientist,

00:09:53.080 --> 00:09:54.080
data analyst.

00:09:54.080 --> 00:09:56.679
So it's free to get it, so you can read the code.

00:09:56.679 --> 00:10:03.599
That's really, there's real benefit to that kind of model for building and making software.

